{
  "texts": [
    "Moreover, the methods of PL and MCDA are transforming the input preference information in a different way and introduce some instrumental bias in interactive steps, thus leading to different results.",
    "Furthermore, the concept of \"learning\" is implemented in PL and MCDA in different ways.",
    "In MCDA, especially in ROR, learning does not only concern the preference model but also the decision maker.",
    "Since the progress in learning of the DM is non-measurable, an experimental comparison of different methods is ill-founded.",
    "Consequently, instead of providing an empirical comparison, our aim is rather to identify methodological and conceptual differences as well as similarities, thereby revealing possible synergies and areas of mutual fertilization."
  ]
}